description:
Review of crates/fsci-interpolate/src/lib.rs on 2026-04-23.

RbfInterpolator::new (line 2577-2634) has a DoS vector (O(n²) allocation with
no sanity check) AND no NaN/Inf validation on points / values / epsilon inputs.

Issue 1 -- O(n²) allocation without bound (DoS):

    // Build the RBF matrix: Φ[i,j] = φ(||points[i] - points[j]||)
    let mut phi = vec![vec![0.0; n]; n];      // line 2614
    for i in 0..n {
        for j in 0..n {
            let r = euclidean_dist(&points[i], &points[j]);
            phi[i][j] = rbf_eval(kernel, r, epsilon);
        }
    }

    let weights = solve_dense_system(&mut phi_mut, &mut values_mut)?;  // O(n^3)

For n = 100,000 points: 10^10 * 8 bytes = 80 GB allocation. Immediate OOM.
For n = 50,000: 20 GB, still OOM-class on most machines.

Comparison with scipy.interpolate.RBFInterpolator:
- scipy also uses O(n^2) memory BUT has explicit documentation warning users
  and a `neighbors` parameter to use only the k nearest neighbors per point,
  cutting memory to O(n*k).
- Our implementation has no neighbors parameter and no warning.
- Our implementation has no pre-allocation size check.

A legitimate user with 10_000 uniformly-distributed 3D data points hits a
~800 MB allocation on a machine with 16 GB RAM -- tolerable but not obvious
from the API. An adversarial caller with 100_000 points OOMs the process.

Issue 2 -- no input validation:

No check that `points[i]` or `values[i]` are finite:
- If any point contains NaN, euclidean_dist returns NaN for that pair,
  Φ matrix has NaN entries, solve_dense_system produces NaN weights, and
  all eval() calls return NaN. Silent failure.
- If `values` contains NaN, same result via the linear-system RHS.
- If `epsilon` is NaN, `rbf_eval` returns NaN (e.g., Gaussian kernel:
  (-(NaN * r)^2).exp() = NaN). Silent propagation.
- If `epsilon` is Inf, Gaussian/Multiquadric kernels produce Inf/NaN.

Compare with the rest of fsci-interpolate which DOES validate (interp1d
checks is_finite at line 131, Interp1d::new handles NaN x_new at line 156).
RbfInterpolator is inconsistent with its own crate's validation discipline.

Issue 3 -- rbf_eval NaN fall-through:

    RbfKernel::ThinPlateSpline => {
        if r < 1e-30 { 0.0 } else { r * r * r.ln() }
    }

For NaN r: `NaN < 1e-30` is false, so computes `NaN * NaN * NaN.ln()` = NaN.
No explicit NaN handling. Same fail-open class as i9vw / y0z8 / 4q0g / 48tv.

Impact:

1. DoS from untrusted point count. Any service accepting user-specified point
   counts can be OOM'd with n = sqrt(available_ram / 8) points.

2. Silent NaN propagation from any NaN-containing input -- same pattern as
   the widespread NaN-fail-open class (4q0g/48tv). User sees NaN output
   from successful-looking Ok(()) construction + eval chain.

3. Inconsistency within fsci-interpolate: Interp1d / PchipInterpolator /
   CubicSplineStandalone all validate is_finite on x; RbfInterpolator does
   not. Users reading the crate get mixed signals about whether inputs are
   validated.

Fix:

1. Add a memory-budget sanity check:
       const MAX_RBF_POINTS: usize = 4096;  // 128 MiB matrix at 8B/f64
       if n > MAX_RBF_POINTS {
           return Err(InterpError::InvalidArgument {
               detail: format!("RbfInterpolator: point count {n} exceeds sanity bound {MAX_RBF_POINTS}; use neighbors mode or reduce input"),
           });
       }

2. Add is_finite validation:
       for (i, point) in points.iter().enumerate() {
           if point.iter().any(|v| !v.is_finite()) {
               return Err(InterpError::NonFiniteX);  // or a new variant
           }
       }
       if values.iter().any(|v| !v.is_finite()) {
           return Err(InterpError::InvalidArgument { detail: "values must be finite".to_string() });
       }
       if !epsilon.is_finite() || epsilon <= 0.0 {
           return Err(InterpError::InvalidArgument { detail: "epsilon must be finite and positive".to_string() });
       }

3. Consider adding a `neighbors` parameter (scipy-parity) for large-n use:
       pub fn new_neighbors(..., neighbors: Option<usize>) -> Self { ... }
   This is a feature addition, not strictly a bug fix.

Regression tests:
    RbfInterpolator::new(&points_with_100k, ...)           -> Err (after sanity bound)
    RbfInterpolator::new(&[[f64::NAN, 1.0]], &[0.0], ...)  -> Err
    RbfInterpolator::new(&[[1.0]], &[f64::NAN], ...)       -> Err
    RbfInterpolator::new(&[[1.0]], &[0.0], Gaussian, NaN)  -> Err

Related: 42z1 (mmread O(n²) allocation DoS -- SAME class at I/O layer),
4q0g (ndimage sigma NaN fail-open), 48tv (signal NaN fail-open), n240
(cluster adjusted_rand_score OOM via max(labels)+1). Pattern: heavy-compute
functions allocating O(n^k) matrices without sanity bounds, plus no
NaN guards on f64 parameters.

Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:3156:

    (&"labels", ClusterObserved::Labels(got)) => {
        let exp: Vec<usize> = case.expected.value...;
        if exp == *got {
            (true, ...)
        } else {
            (false, format!("labels mismatch: expected {exp:?}, got {got:?}"))
        }
    }

Issue: cluster LABELINGS are permutation-invariant. A k-means that produces [0, 1, 1, 2, 0] is IDENTICAL to one that produces [1, 2, 2, 0, 1] (just with cluster IDs relabeled). The current comparator treats these as different.

Current fixture (FSCI-P2C-009_cluster_core.json) only uses kind='labels' for DETERMINISTIC cluster functions:
    fcluster_single_2groups: fcluster with known threshold -> canonical label order
    fcluster_complete_3groups: same
    leaves_list_5pt: leaves_list returns a permutation in deterministic tree-walk order

These 3 cases pass because the Rust impl happens to label in the same order as scipy's. But the comparator is a latent bomb:
1. The moment a fuzz target (per frankenscipy-plyj / 83b8) or fixture extension adds a kmeans case with kind='labels', the comparator will flip pass -> fail on any rerun because kmeans initialization varies with rand seed (especially now that we bumped rand 0.10).
2. Similarly, dbscan label IDs are permutation-equivalent. Current fixture has dbscan scalar metrics (silhouette etc.) but not labels directly -- any future expansion will hit this.

Fix options:
1. Replace exact equality with partition equivalence:
       fn labelings_equivalent(lhs: &[usize], rhs: &[usize]) -> bool {
           // Compute cluster-id correspondence via Hungarian matching on a co-occurrence table
           // OR canonicalize both via 'first occurrence' renaming.
       }
2. Simpler approach that covers 90% of cases: canonicalize labels by 'first-occurrence order'. Relabel so cluster containing index 0 is cluster 0, etc.
3. For metrics where permutation matters (e.g. fcluster with explicit threshold), keep exact equality and tag the case with 'deterministic_labels': true so reviewers know the case relies on label-id stability.

Also: the kmeans centroid ordering has the same problem. compare_cluster_outcome's 'vq_result' branch at 3195 uses exact  and numeric tolerance on exp_dists -- codes are the cluster assignments and inherit the same permutation-invariance issue.

Related: plyj (stats fuzz), 83b8 (no seed corpus for fuzz), d09k (inline tolerance sites).

Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:7659-7670 on 2026-04-22:

The docstring on run_differential_test:

    /// Run a differential conformance test against a fixture file.
    ///
    /// This is the generic entry point for the conformance harness. It:
    /// 1. Loads and parses the fixture file
    /// 2. Detects the fixture type (validate_tol, linalg_core, etc.)
    /// 3. Runs the Rust implementation against each case
    /// 4. Optionally runs the Python/SciPy oracle for comparison
    /// 5. Computes max_diff between Rust and expected outputs per case
    ///
    /// If the oracle is unavailable and 'oracle_config.required == false',
    /// the report marks oracle_status as 'Missing' and still validates
    /// against the fixture's embedded expected values.

Per my bead ivg5: 11 of 12 family runners NEVER invoke the Python oracle. Only run_differential_stats (since today) does. Every other runner skips step 4 entirely -- they probe scipy availability but never shell out to run a scipy_*_oracle.py script.

A reviewer reading this docstring would reasonably conclude that all 12 families perform differential comparison against scipy when scipy is available. That conclusion is wrong for 11 of them.

Fix:
1. Update the docstring to honestly describe current behavior:
       /// ... STATS runner invokes scipy_stats_oracle.py when available; all
       /// other family runners currently use fixture-embedded expected values
       /// for comparison. oracle_status field reports probe result but does
       /// not drive the pass/fail decision for non-stats families. Track
       /// frankenscipy-ivg5 for the broader wiring work.
2. Ideally: fix ivg5 (wire oracles to every runner) so the docstring becomes accurate instead of documenting a temporary state.

Related: ivg5 (the core bug), di9p (10 missing oracle scripts), cpgl (stats oracle landed today).

Review of crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs:6950-6955:

    fn allclose_scalar(actual: f64, expected: f64, atol: f64, rtol: f64) -> bool {
        if actual.is_nan() && expected.is_nan() {
            return true;
        }
        (actual - expected).abs() <= atol + rtol * expected.abs()
    }

This function is the PRIMARY comparator used across EVERY differential_<family>_case_differential in crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs (integrate, stats, linalg, fft, special, sparse, signal, opt, cluster, spatial, ndimage). Verified call sites at lines 2039, 2581, 2624, 5387, 5414, and many more (grep -nE allclose_scalar crates/fsci-conformance/src/lib.rs).

Bugs vs numpy.allclose (verified via numpy 2.4 reference):

Case                          | fsci returns | numpy returns | Correct
----------------------------- | ------------ | ------------- | -------
allclose_scalar(+inf, +inf)   | **false**    | True          | numpy
allclose_scalar(-inf, -inf)   | **false**    | True          | numpy
allclose_scalar(+inf, -inf)   | **true**     | False         | numpy (INVERTED)
allclose_scalar(-inf, +inf)   | **true**     | False         | numpy (INVERTED)
allclose_scalar(NaN, NaN)     | true         | False (def)   | divergent (equal_nan=True semantics)
allclose_scalar(NaN, 5.0)     | false        | False         | OK
allclose_scalar(+inf, 1e308)  | false        | False         | OK
allclose_scalar(5.0, 5.0)     | true         | True          | OK

Root cause: (INF - INF) in IEEE 754 is NaN, and NaN <= x is false for all x. Meanwhile (INF - -INF) = INF, which is <= INF + rtol * INF = INF — always true. So the comparator INVERTS the equality logic for opposite-sign infinities.

Impact:
- Rust implementation correctly returning +INF (e.g., gamma(-n) → +INF per standard convention; 1/0+ → +INF) when oracle also returns +INF: comparator reports MISMATCH and flags the case as a conformance failure.
- Rust returning +INF and oracle returning -INF (catastrophic sign flip): comparator reports MATCH, hiding the bug.
- The existing open beads d218 (complex_gammaln at poles) and jthj (wrightomega underflow) both involve infinity in outputs — their effects on conformance are undetermined because the comparator cannot correctly judge infinity.

Fix:
    fn allclose_scalar(actual: f64, expected: f64, atol: f64, rtol: f64) -> bool {
        if actual.is_nan() || expected.is_nan() {
            return actual.is_nan() && expected.is_nan();  // or false per numpy default
        }
        if actual.is_infinite() || expected.is_infinite() {
            // IEEE 754 equality: +inf == +inf and -inf == -inf; +inf != -inf.
            return actual == expected;
        }
        (actual - expected).abs() <= atol + rtol * expected.abs()
    }

Also: document whether NaN-matches-NaN is the intended convention (the current code says yes at line 6951-6953, which diverges from numpy's default equal_nan=False). If yes, say so in DISCREPANCIES.md (per ma1a bead) so users of the conformance dashboard understand the semantic.

Regression tests:
    assert!(allclose_scalar(f64::INFINITY, f64::INFINITY, 1e-8, 1e-5));
    assert!(!allclose_scalar(f64::INFINITY, f64::NEG_INFINITY, 1e-8, 1e-5));
    assert!(allclose_scalar(f64::NEG_INFINITY, f64::NEG_INFINITY, 1e-8, 1e-5));
    assert!(!allclose_scalar(f64::INFINITY, 1e308, 1e-8, 1e-5));

Related: 37ip (no per-function tolerance contract), m9jp/pqka (other oracle correctness bugs that feed into this comparator), d218 (complex_gammaln returns inf at poles -- exposes both this bug and d218 simultaneously).

Review of crates/fsci-special/src/elliptic.rs:655-662:

    if z.im == 0.0 {
        if z.re > 0.0 {
            return exp1_scalar(z.re, mode).map(Complex64::from_real);
        }
        if z.re < 0.0 {
            return expi_scalar(-z.re, mode).map(|value| Complex64::new(-value, -PI));
        }
    }

The reflection E₁(-x ± 0i) = -Ei(x) ∓ iπ must differentiate the ±0 imaginary part. Current impl unconditionally returns `(-Ei(x), -π)` regardless of whether z.im is +0 or -0, because `z.im == 0.0` matches both in Rust.

Verification (scipy reference):
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-1,  0.0)) = (-1.895..., -π)   (our code correct)
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-1, -0.0)) = (-1.895..., +π)   (our code returns -π, WRONG)
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-2,  0.0)) = (-4.954..., -π)
    scipy.special.exp1(complex(-2, -0.0)) = (-4.954..., +π)   (our code returns -π)

Fix:
    let sign_pi = if z.im.is_sign_negative() { PI } else { -PI };
    return expi_scalar(-z.re, mode).map(|value| Complex64::new(-value, sign_pi));

Related: same ±0 pattern as 276r (complex_sqrt). Both affect conjugation symmetry:
  exp1(z.conj()) should equal exp1(z).conj(); current impl violates this for z on (-∞, 0).

Note: expi_complex_scalar at lines 767-769 delegates to expi_scalar for z.im == 0.0 (returning a purely real value); this IS CORRECT for expi — verified that scipy.special.expi(-1 ± 0i) = -0.219... with zero imag, so no ±0 distinction needed for expi.

Related: 276r (complex_sqrt -0), 0acr (fuzz EdgeF64 lacks ±0 imag sweep), tmti (new complex fuzz harness).

Review of crates/fsci-integrate/src/validation.rs on 2026-04-22.

All three public tolerance/step validators silently accept NaN. Each uses a strict comparison predicate that NaN fails (returns false), so the 'reject' branch is never taken and NaN flows through as an Ok value.

Verified empirically (rustc --edition=2024 probe):

    validate_first_step(NaN, 0, 1):   reject1=false reject2=false => passes: true
    validate_max_step(NaN):            reject=false                => passes: true
    validate_tol rtol=NaN:             clamp=false (NOT clamped => NaN flows through)
    validate_tol atol=NaN:             reject=false (NOT rejected => NaN flows through)

Site-by-site:

1. validate_first_step (line 161-202):
       if first_step <= 0.0 { reject as FirstStepMustBePositive }
       if first_step > (t_bound - t0).abs() { reject as FirstStepExceedsBounds }
   NaN <= 0.0 is false. NaN > anything is false. Both checks are skipped; NaN is returned as Ok.

2. validate_max_step (line 204-223):
       if max_step <= 0.0 { reject as MaxStepMustBePositive }
   Same pattern. NaN max_step returned as Ok.

3. validate_tol (line 225-288):
       let needs_clamp = rtol.clone().any(|x| x < MIN_RTOL);   // NaN < MIN_RTOL is false
       ... rtol.map(|x| x.max(MIN_RTOL))                         // NaN.max(MIN_RTOL) returns NaN (not MIN_RTOL)
       if atol.clone().any(|x| x < 0.0) { reject as AtolMustBePositive } // NaN < 0.0 is false
   NaN rtol: not clamped (predicate false), then the conditional clamp branch isn't taken, so NaN is returned unchanged. Even if f64::max were called, f64::max(NaN, MIN_RTOL) returns NaN in IEEE 754 semantics on most platforms.
   NaN atol: not rejected.

The existing test at line 423-435 DOCUMENTS this as 'appropriate behavior':

    // 8. NaN input in atol -> appropriate behavior
    // NaN is not < 0 so it passes the negative check but is pathological
    // NaN passes the any(|x| x < 0.0) check because NaN < 0.0 is false
    assert!(report.is_ok());

This is a pinning test that enshrines a bug rather than catching it. The comment acknowledges 'pathological' but asserts Ok anyway.

Impact:

1. Hardened-mode fail-closed contract violated. In Hardened mode, NaN in ANY input tolerance or step size should fail closed with an audit-ledger record. Today, NaN tolerances produce corrupt error estimates downstream (NaN * 1.0 = NaN in RK error norm), which makes the adaptive step controller emit NaN step sizes, which propagates NaN through y, which silently returns success: false OR Ok with NaN-filled y. Either way: no fail-closed audit trail.

2. solve_ivp's outer shell DOES check t0/tf for NaN (api.rs:798) and y0 elements (api.rs:809) unconditionally -- so span and initial state are protected. But rtol, atol, first_step, and max_step are NOT checked at the outer shell; they delegate to the broken validators.

3. solve_ivp_impl (api.rs:826-832) calls validate_tol_with_audit passing options.rtol/options.atol unchecked. NaN rtol/atol silently passes and reaches the RK45 step controller. The solver then produces NaN y-values with a success=true report.

4. The four validate_* public re-exports (lib.rs:33-38) are callable directly from user code. A user relying on validate_first_step(NaN) to reject is given the NaN back as Ok(NaN).

5. Interacts with xo4o / 95ld / mhuk: even if Hardened mode were wired through to fsci-integrate (95ld fixes mode: String dead-field bug), the validator itself wouldn't reject NaN in Hardened mode because Hardened-vs-Strict doesn't gate the comparison predicate -- only the audit-ledger record for rtol clamping uses mode. The NaN fall-through is mode-independent.

Fix:

1. Replace strict '<=' / '<' checks with is_finite-first predicates. E.g.:

    pub fn validate_first_step_with_audit(
        first_step: f64, t0: f64, t_bound: f64,
        audit_ledger: Option<&SyncSharedAuditLedger>,
    ) -> Result<f64, IntegrateValidationError> {
        if !first_step.is_finite() || first_step <= 0.0 {
            record_fail_closed(audit_ledger, &fp, "first_step_not_finite_or_non_positive", "rejected");
            return Err(IntegrateValidationError::FirstStepMustBePositive);  // or a new NonFiniteFirstStep variant
        }
        if first_step > (t_bound - t0).abs() { ... }
        Ok(first_step)
    }

2. validate_max_step: same fix. !max_step.is_nan() && max_step > 0.0 (Inf is legit and has a dedicated test, so don't reject Inf).

3. validate_tol: add NaN rejection branch BEFORE the clamp predicate:

    if rtol.clone().any(|x| x.is_nan()) {
        record_fail_closed(audit_ledger, &fp, "rtol_is_nan", "rejected");
        return Err(IntegrateValidationError::RtolNaN);  // new variant
    }
    if atol.clone().any(|x| x.is_nan()) {
        record_fail_closed(audit_ledger, &fp, "atol_is_nan", "rejected");
        return Err(IntegrateValidationError::AtolNaN);  // new variant
    }

4. Rewrite test_validation_tol_nan_atol at line 423-435 to assert_err! instead of assert.is_ok. Update test comment to describe correct behavior.

5. Add regression tests for each site:
    - validate_first_step(f64::NAN, 0, 1) should Err
    - validate_max_step(f64::NAN) should Err
    - validate_tol with NaN rtol should Err
    - validate_tol with NaN atol should Err
    - solve_ivp with rtol=NaN, mode=Hardened should Err with audit-ledger entry

6. Add NonFiniteFirstStep, NonFiniteMaxStep, NonFiniteRtol, NonFiniteAtol (or unified NonFiniteTolerance) variants to IntegrateValidationError.

Related: xo4o (Hardened coverage 2.9%), 95ld (mode: String field dead for integrate), mhuk (audit ledger not emitted for integrate via differential runner), 0v02 (integrate runner ignores mode). This bead is the INNERMOST of the Hardened stack: the validator itself is fail-open.

Review-mode audit of crates/fsci-special/src/convenience.rs:1987-2010:

    pub fn wrightomega_scalar(z: f64) -> f64 {
        let mut w = if z > 1.0 { z - z.ln() }
                    else if z > -2.0 { z.exp() / (1.0 + z.exp()) }
                    else { z.exp() };  // underflows to 0 for z <~ -745
        for _ in 0..50 {
            if w <= 0.0 { w = 1e-15; }           // <-- BUG
            let residual = w + w.ln() - z;
            if residual.abs() < 1e-15 { break; }
            w -= residual / (1.0 + 1.0 / w);
        }
        w
    }

Issue: for z in [-∞, -ln(MAX)] ≈ z ≤ -709, `z.exp()` underflows to 0. Newton loop then sees `w <= 0` and clamps to 1e-15, which becomes the 'answer' after iteration doesn't move much (because f'(w) = 1 + 1/w ≈ 1e15 for w = 1e-15, so Newton steps are tiny).

Verification vs scipy:
    scipy.special.wrightomega(-100)  = 3.72e-44   (CORRECT — Ω(z) ≈ exp(z) for z << 0)
    scipy.special.wrightomega(-20)   = 2.06e-09
    scipy.special.wrightomega(-800)  = 0.0         (underflow is fine here)
    our impl likely returns ~1e-15 for z in [-750, -25], off by up to 30+ orders of magnitude.

The clamp 'if w <= 0.0 { w = 1e-15; }' is doctrine-incompatible: fsci-special must fail-closed, not silently substitute wrong values.

Impact:
- Any downstream function calling wrightomega for deeply-negative arguments silently gets a catastrophically wrong result.
- wrightomega_complex_scalar (line 2022-2024) delegates to wrightomega_scalar for z.im == 0, inheriting the bug.

Fix:
1. Remove the clamp. When initial w is 0 (from underflow), Newton can't iterate (ln(0) = -inf) — detect this and return a Correct limiting value: for z << 0, Ω(z) ≈ z.exp() (including 0 if truly underflowed). Otherwise use a more careful scheme (e.g. log-domain Newton) that avoids representing w directly in f64.
2. Alternative: use scipy's Lawrence-Corless-Jeffrey iteration (arxiv:1501.02813) which handles the full range without underflow artifacts.
3. Add a convergence check at loop end: if |residual| is still > 1e-15 * max(1, |z|), return NaN or Err per mode doctrine.

Regression test suggestion:
    assert!((wrightomega_scalar(-100.0) / 3.72e-44 - 1.0).abs() < 1e-3);
    assert!((wrightomega_scalar(-20.0)  / 2.06e-09 - 1.0).abs() < 1e-6);
    assert_eq!(wrightomega_scalar(-800.0), 0.0);

Related: 276r (complex_sqrt -0 bug), tmti (new complex fuzz harnesses).

Review of commit 1f3fd66 (br-frankenscipy-wo5w relax stats fit fuzz invariant) on 2026-04-22:

The fix correctly resolves wo5w's panic on Exponential::fit(all zeros) = +Inf. But it goes further: it REMOVES the assert_params invariant checks entirely and replaces all 20 per-distribution assertions with std::hint::black_box():

Before:
    let normal = Normal::fit(data);
    assert_params('Normal', &[normal.loc, normal.scale]);
    let student = StudentT::fit(data);
    assert_params('StudentT', &[student.df]);
    ... (18 more)

After:
    black_box(Normal::fit(data));
    black_box(StudentT::fit(data));
    ... (18 more black_box calls)

black_box prevents the compiler from optimizing away the fit() call but adds NO invariant check. The harness now verifies ONE property: 'fit() does not panic'. Per /testing-fuzzing skill oracle hierarchy:
    Strength 1: Reference implementation (scipy parity)
    Strength 2: Shadow model
    Strength 3: Round-trip inverse
    Strength 4: Metamorphic relation  <-- original intent via assert_params
    Strength 5: Crash detector         <-- current behavior

The fix regresses from strength-4 to strength-5. Consequences:

1. A bug in Normal::fit that returns {loc: NaN, scale: 5.0} (mixed
   finite+NaN -- per standard convention, degenerate output) is NOT
   caught. Original assert_params would have flagged it because
   [NaN, 5.0] is neither all-finite nor all-NaN.

2. A bug in Weibull::fit that returns {c: Inf, scale: NaN} is NOT
   caught. Previously caught by assert_params.

3. For 20 distributions, we've lost the 'output is structurally
   valid' invariant. Only raw panic-survival remains.

The RIGHT fix would be per-distribution invariants:
    fn assert_fit_valid_for_normal(loc: f64, scale: f64) {
        // Both finite, scale >= 0, OR both NaN (degenerate data).
        let both_finite = loc.is_finite() && scale.is_finite() && scale >= 0.0;
        let both_nan = loc.is_nan() && scale.is_nan();
        assert!(both_finite || both_nan, ...);
    }
    fn assert_fit_valid_for_exponential(lambda: f64) {
        // Finite positive, OR +Inf (degenerate: all zeros), OR NaN
        // (degenerate: invalid input).
        assert!(
            (lambda.is_finite() && lambda > 0.0) ||
            (lambda.is_infinite() && lambda.is_sign_positive()) ||
            lambda.is_nan(),
            ...
        );
    }

Each distribution's fit contract has a distinct class of legitimate
outputs. A unified 'all finite OR all NaN' wasn't the right invariant;
nor is 'accept anything'.

Fix:
1. Restore per-distribution structured invariants.
2. Delete the now-unused all_finite_or_all_nan helper (already done
   in 1f3fd66, OK).
3. Add regression test: Exponential::fit([0.0, 0.0, 0.0]) = +Inf
   should pass the invariant; NaN-from-bad-input should also pass;
   mixed (NaN, finite) should FAIL the invariant.

Related: wo5w (original bead), u41o (same NaN-to-default pattern in
other harnesses, still open), /testing-fuzzing oracle hierarchy rule.

scipy.signal.buttap(0) returns (array([]), array([]), 1) — np.arange(-N+1,N,2) is empty when N=0, so the −exp(...) computation is skipped and the function silently returns the empty prototype. fsci buttap (crates/fsci-signal/src/lib.rs:2358) instead rejects N=0 with SignalError::InvalidArgument. cheb1ap (crates/fsci-signal/src/lib.rs:2311) already returns the empty prototype for N=0; buttap should match for cross-prototype consistency.

